In TypeScript, you can use type narrowing to tell the type system that a value has a more specific type than what is inferred by the compiler. There are several ways to do this, including:

1. Assertions: You can use the `as` operator to tell the compiler that you are converting a value to a specific type. For example:

```ts
const x = Math.random() as number;
```

2. Type guards: You can use a type guard to check the type of a value at runtime and narrow the type based on the result of the check. For example:

```ts
function isNumber(x: any): x is number {
  return typeof x === 'number';
}

const y = Math.random();
if (isNumber(y)) {
  // y has been narrowed to type number here
  console.log(y);
}
```

3. User-defined type predicates: You can create your own type predicates to narrow the type of a value based on a specific set of criteria. For example:

```ts
const isEven = (x: number): x is even => x % 2 === 0;

const z = Math.random();
if (isEven(z)) {
  // z has been narrowed to type 'even' here
  console.log(z);
}
```

These are just a few examples of how you can use type narrowing in TypeScript. The best approach will depend on your specific use case, so you may want to experiment with a few different techniques to see which one works best for you.

